A.3 Known problems

BurnIT does NOT work with the following CD-ROMs:

Sanyo
Mitsumi FX-001D, FX-001E, FX-300, FX-400
Hitachi

(These CD-ROMs don't support reading CDDA data.)

The following programs need too much cpu and cause errors during writing:

Master Control Programm (MCP)
BlitzBlank (generally screenblankers should be turned off)
StartMenue
Snoop Dos (There was actually someone out there who let SnoopDOS
           run as a background task during writing...)

Oh, and of course BurnIt will not run on a, hmmm, what are
they called, oh yes, peecee.



Appendix B

B.1 Frequently asked questions

Hardware related problems

Q:      I can't reset the logic block size of my Toshiba XM-4101.
A:      You have to turn your CD-ROM off and on once.

Q:      During the write process my SCSI bus gets hung up.
         I have a Blizzard 1230/40/60 with SCSI controller
         or CyberSCSI controller with device version
        8.1.
A:      The device version 8.1 and earlier cause data overflow.
        You have to upgrade to version 8.5+.

Q:      BurnIt won't run on my machine. I have a peecee with a
        Pentium V and 7000MHz.
A:      Get yourself and real computer and stop whining.

Q:      I always have writing errors with my Yamaha 200C/T or
        400C/T and firmware v1.0c, why?
A:      You have to update to firmware v1.0d, earlier firmwares
        are too buggy.

Q:      I always have writing errors with my TEAC R55S and firmware
        v1.0c if I try to write XA data, why?
A:      Update to firmware v1.0f, earlier versions have bugs.

Q:      I always get writing errors with my GVP host (Device v6.0),
        please help me!
A:      Sure, all you need to do is update your device to v6.13.
        
Q:      An error requester pops up if I try to copy in DAO mode. I
        own a GVP controller and a Philips2600.
A:      The GVP controller is rather ancient and does not handle DAO
        commands correctly. Sorry, but you need a new controller.

Q:      The CD I've made with BurnIt are not recognized by the Workbench.
        They're all CD0:ndos. Why?
A:      You're probably either writing in "Emulate write" mode or
        using a wrong block size.


Software related problems

Q:      BurnIT aborts the writing process and/or the CDR contains errors.
        I'm using MCP.
A:      MCP causes write errors because of a cpu usage which is too high.
        Sorry, but you have to deactivate MCP!

Q:      BurnIt aborts the writing process as soon as my screen blanker goes on.
A:      Blankers cause write errors because of a cpu usage which is too high.
        Sorry, but you have to deactivate the blanker!

@NODE CDFORMATS "CD-Formats"
4CH
 Audio CDs have either 2 channels (stereo) or 4 channels (quadro). 
 Theoretically only half of the time of a 2CH CD fits on a 4CH CD if this
 option is set.

@{b}@{u}CD standards@{uu}@{ub}
 There are several existing standards which determine the structure of a CD

@{u}Green Book - mode 1@{uu}
 The Green Book standard defines the structure of a Compact Disc Interactive
 (CD-I). Images, data, full motion videos and audio tracks can be saved in 
 this standard

@{u}Green Book - mode 2@{uu}
 Same as mode 1 except that mode 2 has more data bytes and less error cor-
 rection bytes than mode1.

@{u}Orange Book - Part One@{uu}
 This standard is for Compact Disc Magneto Optical(CD-MO). Data can be written,
 deleted and rewritten. This standard is not compatible to CDRs.

@{u}Orange Book - Part Two@{uu}
 This standard is for Compact Disc Write Once, better known as CDR (CD Record-
 able). The discs can be written, but not deleted.

@{u}Red Book@{uu}
 The Red Book standard is for audio CDs, better known as CDDA (Compact Disc
 Digital Audio).

@{u}White Book@{uu}
 The White Book standard is for video CDs with video and audio data. Normally
 the data is MPEG-1 encoded.

@{u}Yellow Book - mode 1@{uu}
 The Yellow Book standard is for data CDs.

@{u}Yellow Book - mode 2@{uu}
 Same as mode 1, except that mode 2 has more dat bytes and less error correction
 bytes. This mode is used for Photo-CDs and CD-ROM XA.


There are also some special types of CDs:
-----------------------------------------
@{u}Enhanced CD / CD Extra (CD Plus)@{uu}
 This CD standard includes audio and data tracks. The audio track is written in
 the first session, the data track in the second session. The data track is not
 available on a normal CD player.

@{u}Hybrid-CD@{uu}
 A Hybrid CD contains programs and data for Macintosh and PC computers and is
 usable on both systems.

@{u}Mixed Mode CD@{uu}
 Simuliar to Enhanced CD, also contains audio and data tracks. The difference
 is that the data track is written in the first session and the audio track is
 written in the second session.

@{b}CAUTION: Playing the data track on a normal CD player can cause damage to the
         loudspeakers and/or to the CD player. More recent CD players have a
         protection circuit.@{ub}

@{u}Digital Copy Permitted@{uu}
 If the DCP flag for an audio track is set, then it is legally allowed to make
 a digital copy of this track.

@{u}ISO9660@{uu}
 A standard read-only filesystem. Used on many different computer systems 
 (e.g. Amiga, Linux, Unix, Winxx, Mac, MS-DOSE)

@{u}ISO9660 Level 1@{uu}
 The file name length is restricted to 8.3 (xxxxxxxx.xxx). Directory names are
 restricted to 8 characters without .xxx extension. The following characters
 are allowed: A-Z, 0-9, _. Protection bits are not supported. A directory depth
 higher than 8 is not allowed.

@{u}ISO9660 Level 1 + other characters@{uu}
 The file name length is restricted to 8.3 (xxxxxxxx.xxx). Directory names are
 restricted to 8 characters without .xxx extension. All ASCII characters can be
 used. Protection bits are not supported. A directory depth higher than 8 is not
 allowed.

@{u}ISO9660 Level 2@{uu}
 Filenames are restricted to a length of 30 characters. Actually it's limited to
 31 characters, but AmigaOS can only handle 30. Protection bits are not used.

@{u}ISO9660 Level 2 + RRIP@{uu}
 The ISO9660 standard is extended by the "RockRidge Interchange Protocol". Fur-
 ther information on files and directories are saved.
 Filenames are restricted to a length of 30 characters. Actually it's limited
 to 31 characters, but AmigaOS can only handle 30.
 Supports protection bits.

@{u}Joliet File System@{uu}
 Developed by Microsoft, based on ISO9660, this standard supports long file and
 directory names and is Winwuff95 compatible.


@{u}LeadIn@{uu}
 The LeadIn of a track contains all important informations about the track, e.g.
 track type (audio, data), the table of contents (TOC) and the precise postion
 of the data on the CD.

@{u}LeadOut@{uu}
 The LeadOut tells the CD player that it has reached the end of the track.

@{u}Pre-Emphasis@{uu}
 Normally a CD player uses a filter to improve the audio quality of the data
 on the CD. This bit tells the CD player not to use this filter.

UPC/EAN standard

Two different standards for encoding bar codes.

Universal Product Code
UPC is split into UPC A and UPC E.

Both of them consist of a certain amout of characters and a
checksum. UPC A is used to encode 11 characters and a
checksum. The first character is for the system. The first 6
characters identify the manufacturer the following 5 are the
product code.

UPC E is simuliar, except that the zeros in front of the
product code are cut. UPC E is identified by a 0 as the
first character.

EXAMPLE: 07834100009  is turned to  0783419

It's allowed to add 2 or 5 characters as additional code.
These are followed by the checksum.

If the additional code is used, the checksum contists of the
11 characters and the additional characters. The checksum is
inserted between them.


European Article Number
 
The EAN standard is split into EAN 8 EAN 13.

EAN 8 consists of 7 characters, EAN 13 of 12 characters and
a checksum. The EAN contains the product number.

As by the UPC standard, 2 or 5 characters additional code
may be added.
@ENDNODE





@NODE CUEEXAMPLE "CUE-Sheet examples"
Examples for CUE lists in DAO mode
----------------------------------

@{u}@{b}Data CD@{uu}@{ub}
As usual for data CDs the CD consists of only one iso file and one track.

EXAMPLE:
File test:iso.file Mode1  2352
  Track 1
    Index 1  00:00:00


@{u}@{b}Audio CD@{uu}@{ub}
Example 1 shows how to make four audio tracks out of one audio file.

EXAMPLE 1:
File 1 Audio  2352
  Track 1
    Index 1  00:00:00
  Track 2
    Index 1  04:34:00
  Track 3
    Index 1  07:42:42
  Track 4
    Index 1  14:16:65


Example 2 is simuliar, except that Index 0 and Index 1 are used to insert a
pause of 2 seconds in front of each title.

EXAMPLE 2:
File 1 Audio  2352
  Track 1
    Index 0  00:00:00
    Index 1  00:00:00
  Track 2
    Index 0  04:32:00
    Index 1  04:34:00
  Track 3
    Index 0  07:40:42
    Index 1  07:42:42
  Track 4
    Index 0  14:14:65
    Index 1  14:16:65


Example 3 again is very simuliar, except that it shows a CD that can be used as
a master for CD productions according to the Red Book standard.
Every track has it's own ISRC code.
The whole CD is identified by the Catalog entry in the first line of the CUE
list.

EXAMPLE 3:
Catalog 0042285274523
File 49 Audio  2352
  Track 1
   ISRC USPR39507061
    Index 0  00:00:00
    Index 1  00:00:00
  Track 2
   ISRC USPR39507227
    Index 0  04:32:00
    Index 1  04:34:00
  Track 3
   ISRC USPR39609020
    Index 0  07:40:42
    Index 1  07:42:42
  Track 4
   ISRC USPR39609018
    Index 0  14:14:65
    Index 1  14:16:65



@{u}@{b}Mixed Mode CD@{uu}@{ub}
The example shows the structure of CD with a data track at the beginning and
ten following audio track in one file.

CAUTION: Playing the data track on a normal CD player can cause damage to the
         loudspeakers and/or to the CD player.

EXAMPLE:
File 1 Mode2  2352
  Track 1
    Index 1  00:00:00
File 2 Audio  2352
  Track 2
    Index 0  00:00:00
    Index 1  00:02:00
  Track 3
    Index 0  03:14:32
    Index 1  03:16:32
  Track 4
    Index 0  08:16:32
    Index 1  08:18:32
  Track 5
    Index 0  10:35:23
    Index 1  10:37:23
  Track 6
    Index 0  10:46:33
    Index 1  10:48:33
  Track 7
    Index 0  12:31:17
    Index 1  12:33:17
  Track 8
    Index 0  14:43:47
    Index 1  14:45:47
  Track 9
    Index 0  14:52:45
    Index 1  14:54:45
  Track 10
    Index 0  16:15:23
    Index 1  16:17:23
@ENDNODE





